This course brings PHIL together with ENVS. We probably have some students from both directions. (some already double-majors, like Cameron!)

But to the ENVS students: Obviously, you must think PHIL has something to offer...

But back up a minute. WHY??

If we invoke the oldest stereotypes of philosophy... Plato, Descartes, etc... YIKES!

What Dewey said, when pragmatism was praised for doing something great for philosophy, helping philosophy get more grounded practical matters:  NO, the point is that practical matters NEED philosophy. [FIND that quote].

What can PHIL do? 

Well, but first: what IS philosophy???

;It's not a set of texts ("the classics" yadda yadda)
:It's a set of skills.
:At least, that's how I inhabit philosophy.

And those SKILLS will do two things:

(1) blow your mind by opening up new avenues of how things can be perceived and understood. I hope.

(2) Help you avoid some conceptual pitfalls, in a very adaptable way...

What pitfalls? We'll focus on three critical patterns — three ways of recognizing a pitfall from a distance, and steering clear of it. Once you get a strong sense of these, you'll be a much more effective activist, critic, and communicator. 

(a) ECOLOGICAL CRITIQUE means watching out for anti-ecological modeling of the world — ones that make us seem separate from and radically different from our surroundings, humanity separate from the non-human world, etc.
(You're probably already on board... but you may be surprised how many different places we might suddenly discover that people — even environmentalists! — end up taking some kind of anti-ecological model for granted!)

(b) EMBODIED and SOCIAL STANDPOINT CRITIQUE means watching out for anti-ecological ideas about knowledge — what it is, what it does, who has it, how it evolves.
(OK, this is a mouthful. But here's the short version: the idea of "objective knowledge" is kinda anti-ecological, right? Like there's this knowledge that's up in the sky, not connected to anything, and that ideal often invites a kind of arrogance... But then it turns out that if the pendulum swings toward thinking knowledge is *subjective*.... that's ALSO anti-ecological! Instead, we need ways of recognizing knowledge as HAPPENING, in our shared world, in ways that have everything to do with how we orient to life in a shared here-and-there world. 

(c) SUSTAINABILITY and SOCIAL JUSTICE CRITIQUE means watching out for value-attitudes that draw a sharp line around some domain of value — an in-group vs an out-group, near-term results vs long-term patterns of interaction, etc.
Again, I'm probably "preaching to the choir" here... But there are some challenges that go along with sustainability rhetoric, and social justice rhetoric, that will trip us up if we don't see them coming...

a suggested modification of an [[argument]], carried out in the spirit of the [[principle of charity]] (or charitable interpretation), whereby one preserves most of the point of the view under discussion, but with some crucial qualification or adjustment designed to make the [[argument]] more acceptable, especially in light of some [[potential objections|objection]] the author might not have [[anticipated|anticipated objection]].
<hr>
Example: [[Korsgaard]]'s essay (on Kant's rigorism about lying) offers a [[friendly amendment]] to [[Kant]]'s extremely rigorous condemnation of lying. Korsgaard offers a softer version of Kant's position, while seeking to preserve both an appreciation for the reasons behind Kant's own strict view, and a way of assessing potential exceptions without giving way to a bluntly [[consequentialist|consequentialism]] view on the potential permissibility of lying.






:a theoretical approach to problems of combined action, where multiple agents' choices combine to affect outcomes, and those outcomes have different relative values for different individuals.
<hr>
The most famous example of a problem in game theory is called the [[prisoner's dilemma]].

Words, too, decay and scatter; they must give way... there's lots of reflection in Ozeki's novel on whether (and why, how, when) one's words, especially one's written words, disappear... whether Nao's journal should disappear... Archives include both the intentionally-contributed ("jetsam" = jettisoned) and the inadvertently swept up...








: (English term) satisfaction, well-being, or positive subjective experience [but see full discussion below]
<hr>

The term //'happiness'// in English translates various ideas across languages and traditions. (The Middle English word "hap/happe" suggested fortunate or unpredictable events, connotations that still appear more directly in "happenstance" and "happenings".) 

Conflations among different ideas that are associated with this word "happiness" may lead to serious misunderstandings and confusions. 

In particular, many translators choose 'happiness' to translate [[eudaimonia]], the Greek word that refers more holistically to a successful and well-lived life, as measured against the functional standard for the corresponding (usually human) species. This concept is quite different from the subjectively-assessed notion of happiness central to [[utilitarian|utilitarianism]] ethics. It differs, too, from the Stoic ideal of [[ataraxia]].






"Situated Knowledges" is — structurally — a great example of a problem-driven essay.

That is, it...

* begins from a stance of perplexity or confusion
* offers a vivid review of why there's a problem
* gestures toward a potential intervention, synthesis, or resolution

Our first step: ''understand the dilemma''

Second step: Rethink our notions of objectivity as an idealized "point of view"

Third step: Look at the "object" in objectivity... what if there is subjectivity and/or agency there?

: a state of neutrality, or lack of bias and attachment, with respect to persons or situations that are otherwise of equal merit or significance.

''Impartiality'' is a key aspect of wisdom in [[stoic|stoicism]] philosophy, and plays a central role in [[deontological|deontology]] moral theories, such as [[Kant]]'s. Not all [[utilitarian|utilitarianism]] theories  require ordinary everyday decisions to take an impartial point of view ([[J S Mill]], for example, does not). Yet [[utilitarianism]] still implies that moral goodness must be understood from an ''impartial'' perspective. [[Bentham]], for example, is famous for the slogan, "Each to count for one, and none for more than one." [[Singer]] stresses the radical implications of ''impartiality'' for the [[demandingness|moral demandingness]] of morality.






: (in [[virtue ethics]]) failure to act on one's deliberate resolution or awareness of what is best; inability to control or govern one's responses to appetites or emotions, especially with respect to physical pleasures and pains.
<hr>
Antonym: [[continence]]<br>
Contrast also against: [[brutishness]]

The Greek term [[akrasia]] lacks a neat translation into English. "Incontinence" is a somewhat literal translation: lack of ability to contain or "hold in" one's impulses.






Some people place great emphasis on intergenerational links, connection to land, and reverence for ancestors. Such priorities are common among indigenous people.

Other people seem to place less emphasis on these phenomena, valorizing independence from tradition, lack of inherited responsibilities, individual initiative, and mobility of various kinds (geographic, economic, and social).

Could it be that even //this// attitude (a positive attitude toward independence and indifference to ancestry) is also one that is largely passed on through cultural inheritance, bound up with tradition in its own way?

In particular, we might see certain trends in settler-colonial practice as extensions of Protestant religious-cultural attitudes: an inherited restlessness together with an appetite for the new, the independent, and the "uncharted" terrain as opportunities for redemption in the form of individual self-making.

Philosophy is one place where we can pause to question such direct links between information and [[affect]] or attitude.

This polemical bumper sticker might be an effective political intervention in some particular situation... but instead of addressing the normative question (How to feel?) the slogan //suppresses// the question.

: words or gestures that mean one thing at face value, while some insiders (or reflective readers and hearers) are expected to recognize a contrary or more complex implication. 
<hr>
In philosophical contexts, irony is...

* not simply "saying the opposite of what one means," but is rather a way of inspiring ambivalence and further reflection. 
* //distinguished from// sarcasm, which is a cutting tone intended to wound or deter
* //distinguished from// coincidence, confusion, and paradox, which are not forms of communication (We don't say a //fact// "is ironic).

>In the Euthyphro, Socrates openly asks Euthyphro for advice and edification, but Plato's readers recognize that Socrates suspects that Euthyphro has nothing to teach; hence, Socrates' comments to Euthyphro are highly ironic.






: knowledge that focuses not on the representation of facts or truths, but on effective or appropriate paths of action.

:the doctrine that material phenomena account for aspects of reality that are usually //not// understood as material.
----
//Historical materialism// names [[Marx's|Marx]] program of accounting for mental and abstract concepts (ideology) as dependent on and determined by material (economic) relations and interests.

//Philosophical materialism// (or "physicalism," a rough synonym) may also name any stance that rejects mind-body (or spirit-nature or divine-mortal) [[dualism]], in favor of a view on which there is no such division, and all beings partake of material or physical nature.

//Reductionist materialism// maintains, in addition, that nothing has any of the attributes (mind, creativity, intelligence) typically associated with supposedly non-physical (or mental or divine) kinds of being.






: suggestive use of language in which a point is conveyed by drawing attention to some characteristic of a familiar concrete domain (the metaphor's "ground") in order to illustrate something about the domain under discussion (the metaphor's "target"), which is framed as analogous. 
<hr>
Philosophical [[objections|objection]] to particular uses of metaphor can proceed in multiple ways: (1) by opposing the accuracy or significance of the metaphorical connection between [[source and target domains]], (2) by showing that even the metaphor's grounding domain should be understood differently, or (3) by raising concerns about the [[feedback effects|feedback metaphor]] of the metaphor in practice.

If Mind is a phenomenon in which we're immersed, then "mood" might be like a more situated or regional aspect of mind.

Yet "mood" also gestures toward imperatives and values: mood directs us. And this implication seems right: the weather also moves us, animates us with what Gibson calls affordances: opportunities and dangers, demands and prohibitions.

And while Abram speaks of the possibility that a person's mood may be "out of sync" with the landscape, I'm more inclined to think that currents of weather can involve all kinds of turbulence, including eddies and electrical pulses that thrive in bodily fields. So a person being "out of sync" with the local atmosphere is no more anomalous than other micro-weather, (like the surprising turbulence of catfish-mating-swirls on the otherwise smooth surface of a misty morning pond).

If we take seriously the idea that sound waves are in the air, then sensitivity to speech is sensitivity to the weather. (There's no contradiction in the notion that some beings respond to minute differences of weather to which other beings are oblivious.) And indeed, the fact that the weather of a place is, in some sense, shared does not mean that it elicits the same reaction in us all. (Birds pick up on differences of air pressure to which we're oblivious; snakes feel an earthquake coming before our sophisticated seismographs do. English speakers "read the room" in some ways, while Japanese speakers pick up on different patterns...)

What I most missed in the "Moods" discussion was acknowledgement of the social fields of mood. Between "Mood is weather that affects everyone" and "Mood is inside" is "Mood is the local turbulence that catches different beings differently" ... and indeed, between "It's out there" and "It's my private possession" there's "It's part of what I do, and which occasions response from others" ... The way in which a body brings weather toward another body has not come into view.






: a being capable of morally significant choice; someone whose actions are subject to praise, blame, and other moral evaluations.
<hr>
One might think a "moral agent" means an agent who acts //morally// (in the positive sense of acting correctly on moral norms); however, in order to preserve the possibility of //doing wrong//, most moral theorists think of moral significance, or capacity to recognize morality, as giving moral weight to actions, whether or not they are morally good.






Consider these two concepts:

<$details summary="Kant, and many others, claim that these two ideas pick out the same set of beings (namely, rational beings)">

[[Venn diagram]]:

[img width=30% class=img-left [agents|https://www.dropbox.com/s/bpitidvyfrg07w6/kant_and_moral_patient_diagram.png?raw=1]] 

@@.triangle-right Isn't that a fancy way of saying there's no real difference between these two? @@
{{clear-both}}

On [[Kant]]'s view, being able to act on moral reasons is the very thing that makes a being worthy of respect, and hence of moral treatment. In other words, belonging to the set of moral agents is the same as belonging to the set of moral patients... (Kantians will add that we rightly treat a toddler (for example) as belonging to this domain of morality, recognizing the potential moral agent who emerges only with time).
<hr>
</$details>

<$details summary="Utilitarians have tended to have a broader view of moral patients">

[img class=img-right [patients|https://www.dropbox.com/s/z42mo83qjjg61m6/moral_patients_not_agents.png?raw=1]]

The utilitarian criterion for moral consideration is broader; some beings are moral patients without being moral agents... Peter Singer calls for us to "expand the circle" of moral concern.
<hr>
</$details>






:damage to someone's capacity to develop or exercise moral agency
<hr>
from feminist philosophers Claudia Card and Lisa Tessman:

Oppression interferes not only with material wellbeing, but also with moral agency.

Notice this is a volatile point to make, politically!

Some have worried that it seems like "blaming the victim"...

But if you were to seek to reverse-engineer the most effective possible system of oppression, note that it would be especially attractive to find ways to undermine moral agency:

* ways to turn oppressed people against each other
* ways to undermine self-worth
* ways to make it difficult to achieve admirable character traits

Why hasn't traditional moral theory recognized moral damage?

Mostly because of a Kantian legacy:
Kant affirmed that the most important thing about a person is their moral agency
//BUT// luckily, moral agency could not be undermined by any "external" circumstances.

Now, Whyte is not claiming the kind of moral damage that Card & Tessman highlight...

largely because settler colonial powers don't even recognize this dimension of moral agency, so the rhetoric of moral damage would not have much traction.

Hence, the damage is framed in terms of taking away an important aspect of //experience//.

Ingold, however, would be concerned about the bracketing reference to "experience of... "

At least some of Whyte's sources speak more directly about interference with //meeting// responsibilities.






: the endorsement of rigorous obligations that are nearly impossible to satisfy, or which require apparently extraordinary sacrifices on the part of ordinary moral agents.
<hr>
Both [[Kant]]'s ethics and certain forms of [[utilitarianism]] have drawn [[objections|objection]] concerning apparently extreme moral demandingness. 

<$details summary="from Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy">

<<<
The fact that consequentialist impartiality turns out to have such strict and demanding implications is, for the consequentialist, a double-edged sword. On the plausible and popular assumption that a moral theory must be deeply impartial, consequentialism meets this criterion with flying colors. And consequentialists have typically been adept at exploiting this fact with powerful rhetoric (Godwin’s famous query, ‘what magic is there in the pronoun ‘my’?’ being a noteworthy example.) On the other hand, the ''impartial demands'' of consequentialism are so strict and so extreme that many critics have found them unacceptable: consequentialism, they claim, simply demands too much and must therefore be rejected (Scheffler 1982, Slote 1985, Williams 1981).
<<< [[SEP|https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/impartiality/]]

</$details>






: a difficult moral choice — especially one in which any choice would be wrong, either because each choice seems morally forbidden, or because multiple moral demands cannot be satisfied at once.
<hr>
[[Kant]]'s ethics famously argues that genuine moral dilemmas are ''not possible'': every [[perfect duty]] is absolute, but consists simply of a prohibition against hypocritical action (so circumstances can never force one into violating such duties); meanwhile, one [[imperfect duty]] may be in tension with another, but these duties always require judgment as to when and how to fulfill them, and are effectively violated only in patterns of action (such as sustained failure to give to charity), not in single choices.






: a being who ought to be taken into account as //affected// by others' actions; a potential sufferer or otherwise sentient being whose interests or needs have moral weight.

This class offers an introduction to the philosophy of the environment, the environmental movement, concepts of nature, and the place of humanity in the age of the Anthropocene. We will explore a wide range of topics including: changing paradigms of nature from mechanism to biocentrism; the politics and ethics of climate change; environmental challenges to modern political philosophy from feminism; animal rights and land reform movements; ecological and gift economics; monetary reform for sustainability; Buddhist economics and permaculture models of development; media ecology and the transformative effects of technology on the natural world; environmental aesthetics; theory of wholeness and sustainable architecture; comparative epistemologies of nature including ecofeminist, indigenous, and transpersonal perspectives; the study of nonhuman intelligences in nature; nature-based spiritual traditions; and more.

:A central norm governing philosophical [[interpretation]], according to which we read a text (or listen to a speaker) with an eye towards noticing the most [[consistent|consistency]] and reasonable view (by our own lights) it could possibly be trying to express, without ignoring clear differences between the author's [[claims|claim]] and our own.

There are many ways of reading[[*|ways of reading]]. The //[[Crito]]//, for example, certainly has many layers in addition to argument (character, plot, style, cultural insights, political messaging). Yet the most crucial approach to a text, in [[philosophy]], is reading with attention to [[argument]]. The //[[Crito]]// builds a single complex [[argument]] for the [[conclusion]] that  [[Socrates]] was right to accept his death sentence rather than accept his friend's invitation to escape. [img class=img-right  width=35% max-width: 22em [fractal-tree-alpha.png]] 

Noticing the structure of [[argumentation|argument]] in a text is a habit and a skill, built through practice. Like a tree or a river with tributaries, a complex [[argument]] has a core structure (readily recognized from a distance) as well as fine structure that requires close examination.

For a medium-sized chunk of argument, consider the passage that starts around 47a[[*|classic pagination]], and builds toward 48a[[*|classic pagination]], where [[Socrates]] reaches this [[conclusion]]:<br style="clear:both" />

<<<.fm
We should not ... think so much of what the majority will say about us, but what he will say who understands justice and injustice... and the truth itself.
<<< //Crito// 48a

Here is a place to slow down and review carefully: What were the [[premises|premise]] with which [[Socrates]] convinced [[Crito]] of this claim? (Remarkably, this claim is the very //opposite// of Crito advanced at the beginning — namely, that "one must pay attention to the majority.")

Then, in the context of the larger [[argument]], we can notice that the claim above functions as a [[subconclusion]]: how does it fit together with other claims to support the overall [[conclusion]]?

Over the course of the //Crito//, we begin to discern the "main branches" of the core argument. The better we follow the structure of the argument, the better we can evaluate and critique it. Exploring possible critical challenges to an [[argument]] is an essential aspect of constructing [[microessays]] as well as longer philosophical [[writing]].

Crucial [[vocabulary|definitions]] for discussing [[arguments|argument]] include [[premise]], [[conclusion]], [[subconclusion]], [[enthymeme]], [[deductive argument]], and [[inductive argument]].

See also: [[diagramming tutorial]]






This reading calls for one of the most important philosophical <<tag skills>>: 

;__Philosophical [[suspension of commitment]]__ means 
:''//sitting with// a standpoint or line of thought'', and noticing some of its details and patterns, without yet affirming or denying it.

If you're relatively new to philosophy, you might not recognize the gestures, in Ingold's writing, that indicate such suspension is underway.

Consider the "two accounts" discussed on pp. 13-15:

@@.triangle-left Why does the reindeer pause and look directly at the pursuing hunter?@@
{{clear-both}}

<$details summary="Two answers...">

|!Evolutionary biologists' answer... |!Cree hunters' answer... |
|The pausing-and-looking behavior is an adaptation helpful in escaping from wolves|The pausing-and-looking reindeer is offering itself, presenting opportunity to kill|

</$details>

Note what comes next is a "roadsign" moments in the text:

<<<
"Here, then, we have ''two accounts'' — one from biological science, the other from indigenous people — of what happens when when human [hunters] encounter reindeer or caribou. ''__My initial question__ is: how are we to understand the relation between them''?"
<<< Percept of Envir, p 13

At this point, Ingold has not said anything to endorse or resist either explanation. Instead, he is asking:

@@.triangle-left What do we make of this difference between biologists' and Cree explanations?@@
{{clear-both}}
<$details summary="Two responses to this broader question...">

|!Natural-scientists' answer... |!Anthropologists' answer... |
|Science looks for the objective truth about nature, bypassing folklore, superstition, and subjectivity. <br> Meanwhile, the Cree story probably serves to rationalize or paper over the brutality of killing.|The Cree perspective is part of their cultural world of meaning, which must be understood on its own terms; <br> relations with animals, within this worldview, are modelled on human interpersonal relations.|

</$details>

Here, Ingold draws attention to how these two accounts...

*  "might seem ''incompatible''" (14) and yet are
* "nevertheless perfectly ''complementary''" (14)... and ultimately 
* "''converge'' on a common vertex" (15)

By the close of p. 15, if you have successfully made room for [[suspension of commitment]], you'll see that Ingold draws attention to parallel worries about //both// views; what they share (their "common vertex") is bound up with troubling aspects of Western thought:

<<<
[__Answer:__] Both claims are founded upon a double disengagement of the observer from the world. The first sets up a division between humanity and nature; the second establish a division, within humanity, between 'native' or 'indigenous' people people, who live in cultures, and enlightened Westerners, who do not. Both claims, too, are underwritten by a commitment that lies at the heart of Western thought and science... the commitment to the ascendancy of abstract or universal reason. 
<<< Percept of Envir, p. 15

<hr>

: a family of loosely related doctrines (or imputed doctrines), all of which insist that some claim or concept can only be understood or evaluated once a further variable is specified.
<hr>
Clear doctrines of relativism specify what further variable helps determine our grasp of the concept in question. For example: "Cold weather" is a relative concept; in different climate zones, different weather counts as cold." or "Speed is relative; we need to specify a location (on the earth, on the moon, on a moving cruise ship) which is to count as the steady reference point for evaluation of speed." Unclear doctrines (especially when relativism is imputed rather than claimed) tend not to specify: "But if morality is relative, then anything goes." (Relative to what? is a good critical question.)

In //The Republic//, Book VII, Plato offers an allegorical account of captive cave-dwellers, whose "education" (in being brought out from the cave) is initially uncomfortable, but ultimately enlightening. We consider how the metaphor of enlightenment, and various other symbolic associations with Plato's allegorical domain, continue to haunt European conceptions of reality, truth, and value. For our first podcast, we are joined by MJ Rubenstein, Professor of Religion.






;"Environmental" — for the purposes of the course title — means: 
:counteracting the exclusion of the environment.

So we really mean something more like "ecological" — considering anything in a way that does not hack it away from its environment. And that means that we also ought not to go out and study "the environment". Rather, we study a phenomenon in a way that refuses to treat its boundaries as fixed and impermeable, as simply given, as not in process.


cf "feminist" as counteracting the oppression of the feminized... and then what we study is not the "feminine" but gender processes.

In various everyone contexts, we understand that "nature" can have strategically positive uses ("Kids need access to nature"), but we should be wary of essentializing, reifying tendencies that can creep in. Philosophically, we should develop the skill of recognizing how the invocation of "nature" spells trouble. It does not follow, however, that this trouble is always the one at the forefront of our attention.

: the practice or skill of drawing attention to a view or approach, often noting various elements that make the view attractive or logical, //without// yet committing to it.

<hr>
In philosophical reading, allowing for //suspension of commitment// is analogous to //suspension of disbelief// in reading fiction. 

An author may be working //toward// establishing some stance of affirmation or rejection, but without placing emphasis on endorsing or rejecting, agreeing or disagreeing.

How is affect related to time?

Affect suggests a temporal frame bound up with our physiology and attention. With some affective concepts, the link is clear: urgency and vigilance, giddiness and surprise, despair and boredom.

structural integrity in the logic of an argument. 

----
//Note: // To say an argument is valid is to say this: //assuming // that the [[premises|premise]] are (or were) true, then the conclusion must also be (would have to be) true. Sometimes an argument is valid even though it has false premises. On the other hand, an argument may be full of true claims, including a true conclusion, and yet fail to be logically valid.






:A visual tool for illustrating the logical relations among [[categories|categorical logic]] (generally two or three categories) by representing each category as a circle, and each point in space as falling within one or more circles (or, conceivably, outside all of the circles).
<hr>
If the three circles represent the S-term category, the P-term category, and the M-term category, the various colored spaces at right illustrate the potential overlaps between category memberships (Bars over letters indicate non-membership): 

''Conventions''  for marking up a Venn diagram are as follows:

* Hash-marks or shading across a space indicate that the space is empty: nothing "lives" in this category (or intersection of categories).
* An asterisk within a space indicates that at least one item //does// occupy the category-intersection in question.
** When something occupies an incompletely-described space (if, for example, it is both S and M, but may or may not be P), an asterisk is drawn exactly at the border between the spaces it might occupy.

: a character trait associated with the failure to live wisely and well.
<hr>
//Contrast against:// [[virtue]]
In Aristotle's ethics, there were two vices to be contrasted against each [[virtue]]; each vice marked an extreme (of excess or deficiency), while the [[virtue]] required habitual attunement to the mean, or the judicious point of moderation between those extremes. Since [[Aristotle]]'s account is [[eudaimonist|eudaimonia]], vices are never genuinely beneficial to the person who has them, even when they are associated with [[selfishness|enlightened self-interest vs selfishness]] in the narrow sense.

;[[virtue ethics]]
:a tradition in [[ethics]] whose focus is on the activities and character traits of a well-lived ([[eudaimon|eudaimonia]] life.

(Contrast to Kantian focus on [[respect]], [[duty]], [[principles|principle]], and [[intentions|intention]])
(Contrast also to [[Utilitarian|utilitarianism]] focus on impersonal maximization of satisfaction/[[pleasure]]

Examples: honesty, integrity, kindness, generosity, trustworthiness, respectfulness, compassion, (filial) piety, reverence, machismo, humility, ren/jen (benevolence/humaneness in Confucian tradition), chastity, modesty, courage, temperance, industriousness, creativity/ingenuity, loyalty, self-knowledge, strength of will, "will to power", justice, prudence.

Central to most [[philosophy]] is [[reading for argument]]. Yet philosophy texts generally have many layers of meaning beyond explicit [[argument]]. We may find ourselves reading with attention (for example) to how the text offers guidance to readers, or with attention to [[irony]], to rhetorical style, to an author's political or social projects, to problems of [[translation|translation_notes]], or even to what a text betrays, unwittingly, about its author's assumptions or biases. 

In Environmental Philosophy, our attention will focus on reading for [[know-how]] — noticing how authors are //modeling// patterns of attention, suggesting techniques or skills, inviting us to perceive, feel, and think differently. 






[[phenomenology]]

[[dualism]], [[Introduction to dualisms]]

[[transvaluation]]

LIGHT vs SHADOW:

Notice something about Plato's dualisms:

The "lower half" (Spivak's "subaltern") is always //less real//, somewhat //illusory//.

The less real is also more //transient//, more open to change (and what's transient/temporary, what's part of the world of perpetual "becoming" is less real, on Plato's metaphysics, than "being itself" which is eternal, unchanging).

REALITY vs APPEARANCE:

The structuring contrast of Western epistemology — a contrast that invites skepticism and cross-examination, and which rejects contradiction, inchoate plurality, and ambiguity.

Whyte contrasts two framings of Environmental Justice:

<$details summary="standard framing of Environmental Justice">

<<<
The idea underlying this [first] conception of EJ is that justice concerns how the ''distribution of'' certain environmental ''nuisances'', such as pollution, or environmentally related ''harms'', such as asthma in children, burden populations... Environmental nuisances and harms are ... objects or states of affairs for which social institutions bear responsibility either to distribute equitable, or to strive to lessen and, if possible, eliminate. ... (Mohai, Pellow, and Roberts 2009...) 
<<< Whyte, "Indigenous Experience, Environmental Justice and Settler Colonialism"
</$details>
<$details summary="additional dimension of Environmental Justice">

<<<
Injustice ''also occurs when'' the social institutions of one society systematically ''erase'' certain ''socioecological contexts, or horizons'', that are ''vital for ''members of another society to experience themselves in the world as having ''responsibility to other humans, nonhumans and the environment''.
<<< Whyte, "Indigenous Experience, Environmental Justice and Settler Colonialism"

</$details>
